= Intentional Torts to the Person

== Battery

- Definition: 'compromises a direct or intentional [or negligent/reckless] act of the defendant which causes some physical contact with the person of the plaintiff without the plaintiff's consent.' _(Collins v Wilcock [1984] - LE via Rixon v Star City)_ 
  - Every person's body is inviolate, and that any touching of another person, however slight may amount to battery _(Collins v Wilcock [1984] - LE via Rixon v Star City)_

*Physical Act*

- Can be a *direct act* in which the impact followed so closely on the defendant's act that it could be considered part of the act. _(Hutchins v Maughan [1947])_
  - e.g. a log falls off the back of a truck and subsequently hits a cyclist
  - "chain of events": An act will also be considered direct if it sets in motion an unbroken series of consequences, the last of which causes contact with the plaintiff. _(Scott v Shepherd (1773))_

- Can be physical contact such as a strike with a fist but not necessary such as throwing an object, spitting at someone, etc. - all considered direct acts.

- Plaintiff need not be aware of the unlawful contact at time of incident: asleep, unconscious, mental illness, etc.

- Does not need to cause _physical harm_ (see defintiion), but defence can vitiate fault by:
  - implied consent (e.g. physical contact during ordinary course of life or a concert, e.g. jostling of a crowd _(Collins v Wilcock [1984])_)
  - lawful authority - e.g. reasonable force of arrest, prevention of a crime
  - self defence
  - children - reasonable punishment (reasonable needs definition)

*Intention*

- Does not need to be intentional: defendant must have intended, had reckless disregard, or been negligent with respect to the consequences of his/her actions _(McNamara v Duncan (1979))_

- From judcom on intentional torts:
  - _The requisite intention for battery is simply this: the defendant must have intended the consequence of the contact with the plaintiff. The defendant need not know the contact is unlawful. He or she need not intend to cause harm or damage as a result of the contact._
  - _A person who pulls the trigger of a rifle believing it to be unloaded may be found to be negligent, but will not be liable in trespass, because they did not intend that the bullet from the rifle should strike the injured plaintiff. The requisite intention will have been absent._
  - _In most cases, it will be apparent that an intention to make contact can simply be inferred from the nature and circumstances of the striking. If I strike someone with an axe, it will be apparent, except in the most unusual circumstances, that I intended to make contact with the injured person._
  
- Hostile intent is not required to constitute battery; as seen from plaintiffs POV - _(Rixon v Star City)_

- Regarding consent:
 - plaintiff's consent to alleged battery is a total defence to a claim
 - consent may be given expressly by words or implied from conduct
 - a person is deemed to consent to a reasonable degree of physical contact as a result of social interaction _(Collins v Wilcock)_

*Voluntariness (defence)*

- Possible defence is if the act is involuntary such as having an epileptic fit, mental illness, intoxication
 - illness or intoxication requires the defendant to have no conscious knowledge of his action
 - if the defendant knows that he is committing an action, even if mental illness prevents him from understanding the consequences, he is nevertheless liable in battery.
 - negates voluntariness only if the defendant was in a state of automatism as a result of the intoxication or illness

